			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div class='snap_preview'><br /><p>Many recall the tragedies of April 1994.  The Rwanda genocide was one of the most devastating and publicized genocide of the twentieth century.  Almost a half of million people were brutally murdered, the majority Tutsi and the perpetrators were Hutu.  What most people don&#8217;t know is that 20 years prior in 1972 the Tutsi stood on the other side.  They were the perpetrators of a mass ethnic cleansing against the Hutu in the neighboring country Burundi.  It is estimated that somewhere between 200,000 to 300,000 Hutu lost their lives.</p>
<p>There is no real evidence suggesting a true ethnic difference between the two tribes.  Culture, custom and even language was the same.  It was Belgium however during colonialism that identified them into two tribes based upon economic status.  Identity cards were enforced making a person a Hutu or a Tutsi.  Almost as ridiculous as the practice of measuring a person&#8217;s nose during the holocaust, the Belgian&#8217;s decided who was who.  </p>
<p>In October alone there were 206 reported cases of gang related felonies in San Francisco.  When I asked for information regarding gang related shootings or homicides they 1) didn&#8217;t have the information or 2) didn&#8217;t want to give me the information.  I am guessing the numbers are just as disturbing as 206 cases.  Over the years working with youth at-risk I have heard of one shooting after another.  </p>
<p>What&#8217;s insane about both of these cases is that revenge and anger of past violence drives all of the above results.  The average person looks at gang violence and says you need to forgive &#8212; move forward, to end the cycle of violence.  Less people look at the genocide in Rwanda or Burundi and say the same thing.  Even fewer people look at rape or sexual assault and say forgive.</p>
<p>How are any of these cases different and how is one more severe then the other?  They all involve pain, suffering, guilt, revenge and deep-seated anger.  If anything I am going to be controversial and say that rape is less severe.  We didn&#8217;t die, we survived the act.  Hell I would have much rather gone through my 30 minutes than barely surviving a brutal genocide.  </p>
<p>We all fall victim to this thought process at different times in our lives.  I am guilty of not being so nice to different men in my life because I perceived them to be just like my rapist &#8212; they would hurt me and then leave.</p>
<p>Anyways I have gone off on a tangent.  The point is everything we see around us that we identify as violence comes from some other perception of violence &#8212; it is ALL a cycle.  We look at Rwanda and say how sad for the Tutsi and we ignore the fact that they were the perpetrators of the same crime 20 years prior.  We look at gang violence and say of course you are mad he shot your brother (meanwhile conveniently forgetting that you shot his brother before he shot yours).  We look at those who commit rape and never consider the crimes committed against them, or worse yet we look at those who have been raped and make excuses for them.  Poor thing she was raped no wonder she comes to work drunk everyday.  And I am not being facetious I have actually heard these things come out of different people.  </p>
<p>So I ask you all to consider what does it truly accomplish by allowing anger and revenge to reside in your heart.  Does it just cause more violence?  What could change if we were to look at diversity straight in the face and thank it?  Maybe we would have less violence.  Maybe there would be a tipping point.  Maybe we could achieve critical mass.  It&#8217;s your choice.</p>
