			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div class='snap_preview'><br /><p>In 2006 I was taking a class at SFSU on genocide.  When we got to the holocaust my professor brought in a woman who survived the holocaust (she made it out alive) who was now thriving (she spoke regularly to students, wrote a book and appeared in documentaries).  Her story was powerful &#8212; she was just a young girl at the time.  She spoke of one young soldier that showed her kindness while at the Auschwitz concentration camp.  She was able to escape &#8212; but spent several days hiding in a ditch before she could get away.</p>
<p>That day listening to her speak I knew I had to start sharing my story again.  I asked her how she dealt with the memory of everything that had happened and she said she spent everyday working towards it and that sharing her experience was the biggest healer of them all.  When class was over I marched right over to the SFSU&#8217;s SAFE place, the organization on campus that helped those who had been raped.  I sat in the coordinators office and shared my experiences and how I dreamt of a day when colleges had a program as big as take back the night and the clothesline project but with an emphasis on looking at the positive.</p>
<p>Little did I know my co-worker at Harry Denton&#8217;s Starlight Room had a similar vision and was currently a volunteer at the SAFE place.  A few months later we ran into each other on campus, she was heading to SAFE place.  For the first time we really connected.  We had been co-workers for maybe a year but never really talked about what was real for both of us.  Over the course of the next few months we would sit for 20 minutes on Wednesday nights at work and dialogue about my experiences and the possibilities for real healing for others.  </p>
<p>One day she approached me and said I am putting on a program, Turning Negative Into Positive (TNIP) at SFSU and I want you to speak &#8212; and I am going to pay you.  She had just turned my world upside down, I knew I had things to say, but I had never considered before the true value in my story.  The program was a success and my speech was powerful.</p>
<p>Today TNIP has turned into a yearly program at SFSU, a non-profit Create Social Change and an after-school program for youth at-risk that will be launching in the fall of 2009.</p>
<p>Nicole and I are now best friends and each others biggest challenge at the same time.</p>
<p>If Gloria had never been through the holocaust, I wouldn&#8217;t be here today writing to you all.  There is divine perfection in every action or reaction.  If Castro had never taken over Cuba I would not be alive today.  These truths remain the same no matter how small or large the tragedy.</p>
<p>Today I thank Nicole, for being a wonderful friend and a dedicated business partner.  And I look forward to 5 years from now when we can look up and acknowledge the difference we made that stemmed from the staff break room at the Starlight Room</p>
