		<description><![CDATA[Today I picked up a copy of the December 2008 Xpress Magazine.  Mostly because there is a 2-page spread interview of me in it.  The tag line under the article &#8220;Rape on the Rise&#8221; says &#8220;reports of sexual violence in San Francisco are increasing, and one victim chooses not just to survive, but thrive.&#8221;  The [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div class='snap_preview'><br /><p>Today I picked up a copy of the December 2008 Xpress Magazine.  Mostly because there is a 2-page spread interview of me in it.  The tag line under the article &#8220;Rape on the Rise&#8221; says &#8220;reports of sexual violence in San Francisco are increasing, and one victim chooses not just to survive, but thrive.&#8221;  The cover story is an article on bulimia &#8220;A man&#8217;s struggle for identity and survival,&#8221; and the article on the page right before mine is &#8220;A Story of Survival.</p>
<p>Its hard to read these stories.  A few pages before mine a young woman shares about her experience of being molested as a child. The feature story of a young man with bulimia shows several pictures of him still in skeletal form.  Then there are articles on cocaine addiction and a twenty year-old woman with Hodgkin&#8217;s lymphoma.  They are all stories of sadness.  What about the back story &#8212; about the greatness they have all created out of such tragedies?</p>
<p>The young woman who had been molested as a child and taken advantage of by older men &#8212; is finally in her first healthy relationship.  Johnny, the twenty-six year old struggling with bulimia speaks to victims through YouTube.  And Laura, well in a year if there are no more signs of cancer she would be witness to a miracle.</p>
<p>So then why are all these stories focused on the past?  Most people will read these and say &#8220;oh poor&#8230;&#8221;  I have already received numerous apologies about being raped, in fact I hear it every time I decide to announce to someone I have been raped.  The first thing they say is how sorry they are that I had to go through that.  Are people not hearing me, am I giving mixed signals?</p>
<p>I tell them all the same thing &#8212; its pretty much a canned speech.  &#8221;A man broke into my house when I was 17 and raped me&#8230;.when I saw him in court I forgave him&#8230;.today if I were to see him again I would thank him&#8230;&#8221;  What in that statement implies the need for an apology?  </p>
<p>I am hoping some people read this &#8212; and if you do, do me a favor and next time you see me say something like &#8220;well how good for you&#8221; or &#8220;you must be really blessed.&#8221;  Please don&#8217;t tell me how sorry you are for what I have been through, frankly its an insult.  </p>
<p>We have a saying that we share with the volunteers that come and staff a week long summer camp for youth at-risk.  They don&#8217;t need you to feel sorry for them and they don&#8217;t need you to solve their problems &#8212; they have their own answers.  </p>
<p>If these youth at-risk don&#8217;t need us to feel sorry for them when they are dealing with violence, drugs and a failing education system on a daily basis, then why would someone feel compelled to apologize to me over something that happened 10 years ago over a 30 minute time period?</p>
<p>Its time to think differently about challenges.  Think of the butterfly, it must struggle to get out of the cocoon to have the strength to soar&#8230;.</p>
<p>Check out the Xpress magazine for yourself at:</p>
<p>http://xpress.sfsu.edu/magazine/</p>
