			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div class='snap_preview'><br /><p class="MsoNormal"><span>John 16:19</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>&#8220;I tell you the truth, you will weep and mourn while the world rejoices.  You will grieve, but your grief will turn to joy.  A woman giving birth to a child has pain because her time has come; but when her baby is born she forgets the anguish because of her joy that a child is born into the world.&#8221;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>Philippians 3:12</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>&#8220;Not that I have already obtained all this, or have already been made perfect, but I press on to take hold of that for which Christ Jesus took hold of me.  Brothers, I do not consider myself yet to have taken hold of it.  But one thing I do: Forgetting what is behind and straining toward what is ahead, I press on toward the goal to win the prize for which God has called me heavenward in Christ Jesus.&#8221;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>Living in such a religious country &#8212; how is it that we have conveniently ignored what is plainly set out in the bible.  My friend Eric said &#8220;there is always a descent for the sake of an ascent.&#8221;  Is it not common knowledge to the masses that Christ was crucified to ascend into heaven?  If these things are true as are laid out in the bible &#8212; why do we all assume that when something bad happens that there was no God there &#8212; or assume that we are being punished?</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>I was fairly religious as a teenager.  I attended weekly bible studies and went on church trips and praised the lord every Sunday at my local church.  And I remember studying the book of Job.  At the time, I remember being truly perplexed about why God would test Job in the most brutal ways.  I never came to peace about it, I couldn&#8217;t possibly understand why my God &#8212; a loving God &#8212; would cause so much pain and hurt to one person.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>Job 42:10</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>&#8220;After Job had prayed for his friends, the Lord made him prosperous again and gave him twice as much as he had before.&#8221;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>I am pretty sure I denied this line.  We cannot claim that God is Omnipotent, Omnipresent and Omniscience and look at blessings and say thank you God &#8212; but then look at a tragedy over there and say where was God.  If God is Omni then there is an undeniable divine order in all things that happen in any moment.  </span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>If you are an atheist then consider Descartes.  In his third meditation Descartes makes a cosmological argument for the existence of God.  He uses the scientific method of cause having to be equal to or greater than the effect to make his proof.  He ponders the idea of God and tries to find what cause could be equal to or greater than the idea of God.  The only answer he finds it that an infinite substance is the only thing greater than the idea of God.  &#8221;So we shall come to understand that necessary existence is contained in the idea of a supremely powerful being, not by any fiction of the intellect, but because it belongs to the true and immutable nature of such a being that it exists.&#8221;<span>  </span>Something exists and whatever it is or whatever you call it, it is an infinite being.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>Now many of you may wonder why in the world is Chimine:</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>a. Reading the bible</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>b. Sharing the bible with me</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>c. Talking about Descartes&#8230;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>d. What in the hell does any of this have to do with anything?</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>Well in my very warped mind it has everything to do with everything.  Many have heard me say my vision is to be a world-renowned public speaker.  But what on earth do I desire to speak about?  Deconstructing the current taboos, myths, beliefs, etc around violence &#8212; more specifically rape.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>Is it not true that in our world we have been socialized to believe that crime is bad?  Take it a step further &#8212; I was told to not talk about what happened to me and every time I talk about it, there is a moment for the other person where they feel sorry for me.  For what?  Why do we feel sorry for those who have experienced crime, have we not just discussed Job or Christ and descent is necessary for ascent.  Sure that applies but only in cases where the person has come to terms with their tragedy.<span>  </span>Why?</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>People tell me all the time how proud or amazed they are that I have the courage to do what I do.  Why?  I am simply doing what nature intended me to do; I found the blessing in my difficult times.  So why are we so afraid to hold this standard to everyone else around us?  This is where a survivor becomes an activist.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>I am NOT a survivor, I am an activist!  Society tells me to NOT be a victim but to &#8220;take back the night&#8221; and be a survivor.  Why in the world would I take back a night that gave me so many blessings?  I am thankful for that night and I thank a man named Steven Morales for breaking into my house January 8th, 1999.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>So I challenge you all &#8212; consider your tragedies&#8230; Were they really tragedies or were they a blessing in disguise?  If you can find that to be true maybe next time someone tells you about a &#8220;tragedy&#8221; you can look at them and say how blessed you must be &#8212; you are ready to ascend&#8230;.</span></p>
