			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div class='snap_preview'><br /><p><!--StartFragment--></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>So many things happen during the course of our lives.  We have comings and goings, joys and sorrows, pain and happiness, anger and forgiveness.  Sometimes we forget the true blessing in all of it.  I have always said that everything happens for a reason.  I had to believe that.  Mostly I needed it to be true when in the course of 2 months my grandmother passed away and I was raped.  I was only 17 &#8212; this was 10 years ago.  This January 8th I will be celebrating the 10 year anniversary of being raped, and in a few days on November 22nd I will be celebrating the 10 year anniversary of my grandmother&#8217;s death.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>Years ago I never thought I would get over either of these things.  Today I am grateful for these events.  It occurred to me years ago that my grandmother passed so she could be there with me when I was raped.  My grandmother was very religious &#8212; I never was.  And for some reason I knew the words to prayers that day, I said them over and over again in my head.  They kept me safe.  I came out of that day with no true injury, I was so lucky.  In most cases they talk about how as a criminal progresses their crimes get more heinous.  I was the last women, but I was the least hurt, emotionally and physically.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>It also occurred to me many years ago that if I had never been raped &#8212; I may have never realized the power of my words.  Who knew that by being truly violated I could learn to deeply help and inspire others?</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>When I was 10 I gave a speech to my whole school about the Gulf War.  A friend of mine&#8217;s father was in combat.  I had so much to say about it, without even truly understanding what war was.  I forgot about this until recently when my mother reminded me of this.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>Point is, I always had the words and the compassion &#8212; but it took a truly difficult experience for me to embrace myself and my gifts to the world.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>Today I sit here grateful, my grandmother passed so I wouldn&#8217;t be alone and I was raped to learn my own capacity for greatness.  Today I thank them both for the gifts they gave me.</span></p>
<p><!--EndFragment--></p>
